context: Possibly the first house erected within the site was that of a <a0_0><a5_0><b9_0><b13_0>Sir William Blake<b13_0/><b9_0/><a5_0/><a0_0/>, around 1624. The next owner was <a1_0><a6_0><b10_0>Lord Goring<b10_0/><a6_0/><a1_0/>, who from 1633 extended Blake's house and developed much of today's garden, then known as <a2_0><a7_0><b11_0>Goring Great Garden<b11_0/><a7_0/><a2_0/>. He did not, however, obtain the freehold interest in the mulberry garden. Unbeknown to Goring, in 1640 the document "failed to pass the Great Seal before <a4_0><a8_0><b12_0>King Charles I<b12_0/><a8_0/><a4_0/> fled London, which it needed to do for legal execution". It was this critical omission that helped the British royal family regain the freehold under <a3_0>King George III<a3_0/>.
